Multinomial Logistic Regression DrPH Sem 2

Author

Dr Hazlienor Mohd Hatta

Published

July 1, 2024

Multinomial Logistic Regression

Research Question

When high school students choose the program (general, vocational, and academic programs), how do their gender, math and science scores and their social economic status (SES) affect their decision?

Justification for multinomial logistic regression

The researcher would like the study the influence of several factors on the outcome variable. The outcome is polychotomous categorical variable with more than two levels and has no natural ordering. Multinomial logistic regression allows for modeling the probabilities of the outcome categories relative to a chosen reference category.Â 

Alternative

  • Multinomial probit regression, similar to multinomial logistic regression with independent normal error terms.

  • Multiple-group discriminant function analysis. A multivariate method for multinomial outcome variables

  • Multiple logistic regression analyses, one for each pair of outcomes: One problem with this approach is that each analysis is potentially run on a different sample. The other problem is that without constraining the logistic models, we can end up with the probability of choosing all possible outcome categories greater than 1.

  • Collapsing number of categories to two and then doing a logistic regression: This approach suffers from loss of information and changes the original research questions to very different ones.

  • Ordinal logistic regression: If the outcome variable is truly ordered and if it also satisfies the assumption of proportional odds, then switching to ordinal logistic regression will make the model more parsimonious.

  • Alternative-specific multinomial probit regression, which allows different error structures therefore allows to relax the IIA assumption. This requires that the data structure be choice-specific.

  • Nested logit model, another way to relax the IIA assumption, also requires the data structure be choice-specific.

Dataset

The data set(hsbdemo.sav) contains variables on 200 students. The outcome variable is prog, program type (1=general, 2=academic, and 3=vocational). The predictor variables are ses, social economic status (1=low, 2=middle, and 3=high), math, mathematics score, and science, science score: both are continuous variables.

Load Data

hsbdemo <- read_dta("https://stats.idre.ucla.edu/stat/data/hsbdemo.dta")

Logistic Regression Analysis

Estimation

determine the level of DV

reference: general program

we want to estimate the model for

  1. academic (2) vs general (3)

  2. vocation (1) vs general (3)

levels(hsbdemo1$prog)
[1] "general"  "academic" "vocation"

we want to use VGAM package. re-level so the last group is the reference group

hsbdemo1 <- 
  hsbdemo1 %>% 
  mutate(prog2 = fct_relevel(prog,
                       c("vocation", 'academic', 'general')))

re-check level

levels(hsbdemo1$prog2)
[1] "vocation" "academic" "general"

fit model - estimate log odds

mn1 <- vglm(prog2 ~ female + math + science + ses, multinomial, data = hsbdemo1)

interpretation

compared to male, female have lower estimated odds (by the factor of 0.9) to enrolled to vocational program compared to general program, when adjusted for math & science score, and SES.

however, being female has 1.084 higher estimated odds compared to male to enroll to academic program compared to general program, when adjusted for math & science score, and SES.

for every 1 unit increase in math score, the estimated odds of enrolling to academic program compared to general program increase by 1.138, when adjusted for gender, science score, and SES.

for every 1 unit increase in math score, the estimated odds of enrolling in vocational program over general program decrease when adjusted for gender, science score, and SES.
